{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_9e58iwdnz9j9_1","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All three prompts are written to the inbox and validated. Here is the summary.\n\n## Files created\n\n- `/workspace/prompts/1-spec-004-ranking-core-and-delete-decrementor.md`\n- `/workspace/prompts/2-spec-004-scan-and-collapse-hook.md`\n- `/workspace/prompts/3-spec-004-wire-lookback-env-docs-changelog.md`\n\n**Execution order is strictly sequential** (each depends on the prior; both prompt 2 and 3 carry an explicit fail-loud dependency gate).\n\n## Key design decisions\n\n1. **Ordinal replaces decrement (prompt 1).** The old model computed the single arithmetic predecessor via `decrementRecurringTaskTitle`. Scan-and-collapse needs to *rank* an arbitrary candidate set, so I pinned prompt 1 to a pure `parsePeriodTokenOrdinal(token) → int64` (a comparable Unix-time ordinal, larger = more recent) plus a stable `rankSameSlugCandidatesDescending`. The six existing regexes and the ISO-week helper are *moved* (not rewritten) into a new `period_token_ranking.go`; the decrementor file, its test, and the `DecrementRecurringTaskTitle` export seam are deleted, satisfying the AC that greps for zero references.\n\n2. **Same-week weekday siblings collapse via equal-ordinal, not strictly-older.** This was the one real design trap: `-mon`, `-wed`, `-fri` of the same ISO week share one Monday-ordinal, so a strictly-older filter would skip them and the `IBKR Swing Trading` five-stream case would not collapse. I resolved it to a single authoritative rule in step 2f — supersede a candidate when `rc.Ordinal <= newOrdinal` (implemented as \"skip only `rc.Ordinal > newOrdinal`\"), relying on the new instance already being excluded from the candidate set so the equal-ordinal branch only ever matches genuine siblings. I removed the earlier draft's contradictory `>=` and the deliberation prose.\n\n3. **K bounds reads, counted before the read.** The inspected-counter increments before the ReadFile so the \"at most K reads\" invariant holds even across 404s and already-aborted candidates.\n\n4. **Glob-injection defense as always-filter.** `listSameSlugCandidateTitles` uses a slug-scoped glob only when the slug has no glob metacharacters; otherwise it lists `tasks/*.md`. Either way it applies an in-memory `<slug> - ` prefix filter, so the result is always exactly slug-scoped and a crafted title cannot widen the listing.\n\n5. **Reused the frozen helpers.** `isEligibleForSupersede`, `readPriorForSupersede`, `priorIsInProgress`, `transitionPrior`, `buildSupersedeModifyFn` are kept verbatim (prompt 1 stubs the caller no-op to keep the build green; prompt 2 rewrites only the orchestration). The five frozen frontmatter fields, the commit-message substring, and the eligibility gate (`auto_abort_prior`, not `audit_style`) are unchanged.\n\n6. **K wiring split across prompts to keep every build green.** Prompt 2 adds the `k int` parameter through executor+factory and inserts a literal `7` in `main.go` with a TODO; prompt 3 replaces it with the `SUPERSEDE_LOOKBACK` env field (default 7, `>= 1` startup guard) and does the doc/CHANGELOG/scenario. Verified there is exactly one `main.go` caller and no `cmd/` variant. Prompt 2 Req 9 was corrected to name all **five** `NewCreateTaskExecutor` test call sites (64, 359, 378, 397, 416) after grep found the four vault-routing tests each build a local executor.\n\n## Docs referenced in `<context>`\nCoding plugin (in-container paths): `go-patterns.md`, `go-error-wrapping-guide.md`, `go-testing-guide.md`, `go-time-injection.md`, `go-precommit.md`, `changelog-guide.md`. Project docs: `/workspace/docs/period-token-semantics.md`, existing scenario files.\n\n## Open questions surfaced (none blocking)\n- **Scenario decision:** the spec explicitly designates the live Kafka-replay post-deploy check as the E2E evidence and asks to update `scenarios/` supersede coverage. No existing supersede scenario exists (grep confirmed), so prompt 3 creates `scenarios/004-recurring-task-supersede-collapse.md` encoding the spec's `/trigger?date=...` replay — this satisfies all four scenario-writing conditions (real git-rest + Kafka, load-bearing user journey, no existing coverage, named `IBKR Swing Trading` regression).\n- **Verify before executing:** run `/audit-prompt /workspace/prompts/1-spec-004-ranking-core-and-delete-decrementor.md` (and 2, 3) before approving."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a59b3fc0b30aae3fb (use SendMessage with to: 'a59b3fc0b30aae3fb' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 117250\ntool_uses: 42\nduration_ms: 514371</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"39ee2fda-6615-4b39-af19-b21d581ad85c","uuid":"b084a109-df86-4739-af7b-8d5405c5bef1","timestamp":"2026-07-08T09:09:21.383Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"You are the dark-factory prompt-creator agent. Read the spec at `/workspace/specs/in-progress/004-recurring-task-supersede-scan-collapse.md` and generate prompt files for its implementation.\n\n**Context:**\n- Repo root: `/workspace`\n- Output directory: `/workspace/prompts/` (inbox — NOT `prompts/in-progress/`)\n- Mode: non-interactive. Resolve any ambiguity from the spec content itself. If the spec is genuinely under-specified, produce best-effort decomposition and surface open questions as comments inside the generated prompts.\n- The agent has full access to `/workspace/` for reading source files to verify signatures, look up library APIs, and discover existing patterns.\n\n**Your task:**\n1. Read the spec fully\n2. Explore the codebase at `/workspace` to understand existing patterns (especially the existing supersede hook, the GitClient interface, the period token regexes, the fake GitClient for tests, the existing factory wiring pattern for env vars)\n3. Generate 3 prompt files based on the suggested decomposition in the spec (prompt 1: ranking + slug/token parsing + delete decrement m